'''HMS ''Porcupine''''' was a {{sclass-|Janus|destroyer}} of the [[Royal Navy]]. She was launched by [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company]] in 1895, served in home waters and was in service during the [[First World War]].
==Design and construction== Three [[torpedo-boat destroyer]]s were ordered on 7 November 1893 from the [[Jarrow]] shipbuilders, [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company]] for the Royal Navy as part of the 1893–1894 Naval Estimates. These three ships, {{HMS|Janus|1895|2}}, {{HMS|Lightning|1895|2}} and ''Porcupine'' were part of a larger group of 36 destroyers ordered as part of this shipbuilding programme, as a follow-on to the six prototype "26-knotters" ordered in the previous 1892–1893 Estimates.<ref name="Lyon p77">Lyon 2001, p. 77.</ref><ref name="Lyon p19-0">Lyon 2001, pp. 19–20.</ref> The [[Admiralty]] laid down broad requirements for the destroyers, including a speed of {{convert|27|kn}} on sea trials, with the detailed design left to the builders, resulting in each of the builders producing different designs.<ref name="Conways60 p87">Chesneau and Kolesnik 1979, p. 87.</ref><ref name="Manning p39">Manning 1961, p. 39.</ref>
[[Janus-class destroyer|Palmers' design]] was {{convert|204|ft|6|in|m}} [[overall length|long overall]] and {{convert|200|ft|m|2}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]], with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|19|ft|9|in|m}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|8|ft|0|in}}. [[Displacement (ship)|Displacement]] was {{convert|275|LT|t}} light and {{convert|320|LT|t}} full load.<ref name="Lyon p77"/> Four Reef [[water-tube boiler]]s fed steam at {{convert|250|psi}} to two [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple expansion steam engines]] rated at {{convert|3900|ihp|lk=in}} and driving two propeller shafts.<ref name="Lyon p77"/> Three funnels were fitted.<ref name="Friedman p54">Friedman 2009, p. 54.</ref> Armament consisted of a single [[QF 12 pounder 12 cwt naval gun|QF 12 pounder 12 cwt]]{{#tag:ref|"Cwt" is the abbreviation for [[hundredweight]], 12cwt referring to the weight of the gun.|group=lower-alpha}} gun and three 6-pounder guns, with two {{convert|18|in|mm|sing=on|0}} torpedo tubes.<ref name="Friedman p291">Friedman 2009, p. 291.</ref> One of the torpedo tubes could be removed to accommodate a further two six-pounders,<ref name="Lyon p98-9">Lyon 2001, pp. 98–99.</ref> although the Palmer 27-knotters later carried both the two torpedo tubes and all 5 six-pounder guns.<ref name="Lyon p100">Lyon 2003, p. 100.</ref>
''Porcupine'', together with the other two Palmer-built destroyers, was [[Keel laying|laid down]] on 28 March 1894. She was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 19 September 1895.<ref name="Fried p302">Friedman 2009, p. 302.</ref> ''Porcupine'' reached a speed of {{convert|27.91|kn}} during [[sea trials]], exceeding the required 27 knots.<ref name="Brassey97 p321">Brassey 1897, p. 321.</ref> She was completed in March 1896.<ref name="Fried p302"/>
==Service history== ''Porcupine'' took part in the 1896 British Naval Manoeuvres, attached to the [[Channel Fleet]] operation from [[Milford Haven]].<ref name="Brasseys87 p141-3, 9">Brassey 1897, pp. 141–143, 149.</ref> ''Porcupine'' undertook a refit at [[HMNB Chatham|Chatham]] in late 1899, and was passed into the Fleet Reserve 15 January 1900.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=16 January 1900 |page_number=9 |issue=36040}}</ref> The following month she succeeded [[HMS Cygnet (1898)|HMS ''Cygnet'']] as part of the [[Medway]] Instructional [[Flotilla]], taking the latter ship's crew, including Commander [[Cecil Hickley]] in command.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence|day_of_week=Tuesday |date=6 February 1900 |page_number=10 |issue=36058| }}</ref> In 1910, ''Porcupine'' was part of the Sixth Destroyer Flotilla, based at [[Commander-in-Chief, The Nore|The Nore]], still being based at the Nore in 1912.<ref name="nmm">{{cite web|url=http://www.rmg.co.uk/upload/pdf/Warship_Histories_Vessels_iii.pdf|title=NMM, vessel ID 373572|work=Warship Histories, vol iii|publisher=[[National Maritime Museum]]|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref> On 30 August 1912 the Admiralty directed all destroyers were to be grouped into classes designated by letters based on contract speed and appearance. After 30 September 1913, as a 27-knotter, ''Porcupine'' was assigned to the [[A-class destroyer (1913)|A class]].<ref name="Conway06 p18">Gardiner and Gray 1985, p. 18.</ref><ref name="Manning p17-8">Manning 1961, pp. 17–18.</ref><ref name="Ditt p56">Dittmar and Colledge 1972, p. 56.</ref>
By February 1913, ''Porcupine'' was not part of an active flotilla, but was attached as a tender to the torpedo school at [[HMNB Chatham|Chatham]], with a nucleus crew,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Fleets and Squadrons in Commission at Home and Abroad: Torpedo Craft and Submarine Flotillas at Home Ports|journal=The Navy List|date=March 1913|page=270b|url=http://digital.nls.uk/british-military-lists/pageturner.cfm?id=94246590&mode=fullsize|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref> although she was in full commission by May 1913.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Fleets and Squadrons in Commission at Home and Abroad: Torpedo Craft and Submarine Flotillas at Home Ports|journal=The Navy List|date=May 1913|page=270b|url=http://digital.nls.uk/british-military-lists/pageturner.cfm?id=94267982|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref> She remained part of the torpedo school based at Chatham on the eve of the outbreak of the [[First World War]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Fleets and Squadrons in Commission at Home and Abroad: Torpedo Craft and Submarine Flotillas at Home Ports|journal=The Navy List|date=August 1914|page=270c|url=http://digital.nls.uk/british-military-lists/pageturner.cfm?id=91884274|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref>
''Porcupine'' joined the Local Defence Flotilla at the Nore on the outbreak of war,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ships of the Royal Navy - Location/Action Date, 1914–1918: Part 2 - Admiralty "Pink Lists", 5 August 1914|url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW1NavyBritishShips-Locations2PL1408.htm|publisher=Naval-History.net|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref> and remained part of that formation for much of the rest of the war, still being a member in November 1917.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Supplement to the Navy List Showing Organisation of the Fleet, Flag Officers' Commands &c.: VIII.—Local Defence Flotillas|journal=The Navy List|date=November 1917|page=18|url=http://digital.nls.uk/british-military-lists/pageturner.cfm?id=92177146|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref>
''Porcupine'' was sold to the ship breakers [[Thos W Ward]] on 29 April 1920 for scrapping.<ref name="Ditt p56"/>
